that this app is going to
be perhaps slightly less

00:05:12.140 --> 00:05:13.655
responsive than I might hope.

00:05:13.655 --> 00:05:17.190
And it might not follow my
expected mental models.

00:05:17.190 --> 00:05:20.730
Certain things like if you look
at like the Up arrow next

00:05:20.730 --> 00:05:24.620
to the app icon on the second
screen, you can see it's

00:05:24.620 --> 00:05:26.870
slightly too big, slightly too
thick, and all of these

00:05:26.870 --> 00:05:30.020
things, which may seem very
subtle, but they just hint to

00:05:30.020 --> 00:05:32.730
the user that this app is going
to function unlike the

00:05:32.730 --> 00:05:36.330
standard apps which we're used
to functioning with.

00:05:36.330 --> 00:05:38.930
I'm also a big fan of Kayak,
but already there's a few

00:05:38.930 --> 00:05:41.300
uh-ohs going on.

00:05:41.300 --> 00:05:41.636
ROMAN NURIK: Yeah.

00:05:41.636 --> 00:05:43.640
And actually, we'll talk
a little bit more

00:05:43.640 --> 00:05:45.180
about the faux ActionBar.

00:05:45.180 --> 00:05:47.510
There's really no reason to
do it anymore, right?

00:05:47.510 --> 00:05:49.890
I think actually Jake Wharton,
who is the author of one of

00:05:49.890 --> 00:05:52.260
the greatest kind of ActionBar
libraries out there--

00:05:52.260 --> 00:05:53.120
ActionBarSherlock--

00:05:53.120 --> 00:05:55.180
mentioned you're doing
